If you’re going to be forced to return to your wrapped story by the suits (agents), make it your own again and don’t let the bastards box your art in. That’s exactly what Lana Wachowski manages with The Matrix Resurrections. Simultaneously a lament, a battle cry, and an ode, we are once more asked to confront ourselves, our society, and interrogate the choices we have made in the intervening years since The Matrix hit movie theaters like a freight train 25 years ago. The answers will take time, but Lana Wachowski lit a new beacon signaling we can break the chains binding us to reality.

Much maligned by LARGE groups of its intended audience, I personally find THE MATRIX RESURRECTIONS contains MUCH to enjoy.

The meta commentary and lighter (often outright humorous) tone add 21st century trappings to proceedings, whilst the central love story is very romantic. The film also more successfully delivers its its philosophical musings.
The main draw back is the action- it’s just not as spectacular as what had come before. That’s not to say it’s bad- the finale in particular is fierce, but there is a flatness to it.

It's taken a few goes but I think I'm finally starting to see what they were trying to do here. Yes, the meta scenes are clever and self depreciating. Yes, the reunion of Neo and Trinity is what you would expect. And yes, NPH still doesn't fit. But there's something deeper here that I'd missed before about loss, longing, identity (perhaps not actually a surprise given the director's experiences) and an interesting commentary on mental health issues. This isn't The One but it's perhaps better than those other two.

I don’t have a lot of time to write something right now and I should probably watch this a few more times before I can really come up with anything meaningful. However this movie is one of the most sincere, goofy, and beautiful things I’ve ever seen. It’s a movie made with love, a passionate lament of grief, fears, and desires. A movie where love ultimately wins. When others seek to use you, mistreat you, profit off of you, the best way of defeating them isn’t through hurting what you hate but protecting what you love. I love this movie and it loves me too.
Is it perfect? No. Is it fun? Yes!

Going in with my expectations properly set, and I still like this movie. It’s no patch on the original trilogy, with a fairly bland look (in comparison) and some howlingly bad pacing, but I appreciate a big action film in the 2020s trying to recapture some of that 90s magic.

The message, about sequels and loops and retracing steps is interesting, but could’ve been handled in more subtle ways. It’s also a shame that some of the original cast aren’t back to resume their roles - would’ve been interesting to see them with different personalities, and the tension in certain scenes would’ve been higher.

That’s exactly what Lana Wachowski manages with The Matrix Resurrections. Much maligned by LARGE groups of its intended audience, I personally find THE MATRIX RESURRECTIONS contains MUCH to enjoy.

The meta commentary and lighter (often outright humorous) tone add 21st century trappings to proceedings, whilst the central love story is very romantic. The film also more successfully delivers its its philosophical musings.
The main draw back is the action- it’s just not as spectacular as what had come before. That’s not to say it’s bad- the finale in particular is fierce, but there is a flatness to it.

It's taken a few goes but I think I'm finally starting to see what they were trying to do here. Yes, the meta scenes are clever and self depreciating. Yes, the reunion of Neo and Trinity is what you would expect. And yes, NPH still doesn't fit. But there's something deeper here that I'd missed before about loss, longing, identity (perhaps not actually a surprise given the director's experiences) and an interesting commentary on mental health issues. This isn't The One but it's perhaps better than those other two.

The message, about sequels and loops and retracing steps is interesting, but could’ve been handled in more subtle ways. It’s also a shame that some of the original cast aren’t back to resume their roles - would’ve been interesting to see them with different personalities, and the tension in certain scenes would’ve been higher.

RETOUR À LA SOURCE; Retour dans deux réalités parrallèles... celle de notre quotidien et celle du monde qui s'y dissimule. Pour véritablement se connaître lui-même, Neo devra de nouveau suivre le lapin blanc dans la Matrice. Bien entendu, Neo sait déjà ce qui lui reste à faire. Ce qu'il ignore en revance, c'est que la Matrice est plus redoutable que jamais. Comme un air de déjà vu...

Arriving 18 years after the conclusion of the original trilogy, The Matrix Resurrections is a legacy sequel that sees co-writer and director Lana Wachowski return to the series that put The Wachowskis on the map. The film takes some meta pokes at the concept of legacy sequels by having Thomas Anderson be introduced as the designer of a video game trilogy called The Matrix, of which he is being asked by his business partner Smith to create a new sequel.…
